---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ReviewsSection from '../../components/ReviewsSection.astro';

const phone = '01623 325 123';
const telHref = `tel:${phone.replace(/\s+/g, '')}`;

const serviceJsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Service',
  name: 'TPMS Sensor Replacement',
  serviceType: 'Mobile TPMS Sensor Diagnostic and Replacement',
  provider: {
    '@type': 'LocalBusiness',
    name: 'Tyre Emergency Ltd',
    telephone: '+441623325123',
    url: 'https://tyreemergencyltd.co.uk/',
  },
  areaServed: 'Nottinghamshire, East Midlands',
  description: 'Diagnostic, replacement and reprogramming of TPMS sensors for cars, vans and commercial vehicles, carried out on-site.',
  url: 'https://tyreemergencyltd.co.uk/services/tpms-sensor-replacement/',
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="TPMS Sensor Replacement Nottinghamshire | Mobile Diagnostic & Reprogramming"
  description="Mobile TPMS sensor replacement and programming across Nottinghamshire. IMI certified, with the diagnostic and programming tools on board to fit and pair a new sensor to your vehicle on-site. Call 01623 325 123."
  jsonLd={JSON.stringify(serviceJsonLd)}
>
  <section class="service-hero" style="background-image: url('/images/emergency-tyre-fitting.webp');">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">Diagnostic Service</span>
      <h1>TPMS Sensor Replacement</h1>
      <p class="service-intro">
        TPMS work is one of those jobs a lot of mobile fitters won&rsquo;t touch &mdash; we&rsquo;re IMI certified for it, with the tools on board to take the old sensor out, fit a new one and program it to your vehicle there and then. From warning light on to warning light off in a single visit.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn btn-primary btn-call" href={telHref}>
          <span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> Call: {phone}
        </a>
        <a class="btn btn-outline" href="/#quote">Get a Quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <ReviewsSection />

  <section class="section section-white">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow">Read your warning light first</span>
      <h2>What that amber light is actually telling you</h2>
      <p>Knowing what the light is doing can save you a callout &mdash; or tell you to book one in:</p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><strong>Solid amber light</strong> &mdash; that&rsquo;s a tyre pressure issue, not a faulty sensor. Top your tyres up to the figure on the door pillar and the light should clear within a few miles. If it doesn&rsquo;t, give us a call.</li>
        <li><strong>Flashing for about 60 seconds and then going solid</strong> &mdash; that&rsquo;s a fault in the system. Most often it&rsquo;s a sensor with a flat battery (they last around 7&ndash;10 years). That&rsquo;s the one to call us out for.</li>
      </ul>
      <h2 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What you get when we come out</h2>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><strong>Full TPMS scan on every wheel</strong> so we know exactly which sensor has gone &mdash; and we check the others for low battery while we&rsquo;re there, so the same problem doesn&rsquo;t reappear next month.</li>
        <li><strong>Programmable sensors that cover virtually every make</strong> on UK roads &mdash; no waiting for a dealer-only part to land.</li>
        <li><strong>Cloned or freshly programmed</strong> &mdash; we either copy the old sensor&rsquo;s ID across to save you a relearn, or program a new one in and complete the relearn cycle.</li>
        <li><strong>New valve stem fitted with every sensor</strong> &mdash; rubber or metal to suit the wheel &mdash; so it seals properly and doesn&rsquo;t weep air later.</li>
        <li><strong>Light confirmed off before we leave</strong>, with the scan tool reading live data from all four wheels.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-darker">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow">When You Need This</span>
      <h2>The kind of TPMS calls we get</h2>
      <div class="scenarios">
        <article class="scenario">
          <h3>Light flashes for 60 seconds, then stays on</h3>
          <p>Classic dead-battery sensor symptom. Pressures are fine but the system thinks something is wrong. We&rsquo;ll diagnose which sensor has died and replace it on the spot.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="scenario">
          <h3>MOT round the corner</h3>
          <p>Permanently lit TPMS lights are an MOT failure on most cars first registered after 1 January 2012. Get it sorted before the test rather than after &mdash; saves a re-test fee and a wasted morning.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="scenario">
          <h3>Sensor damaged at the last fitting</h3>
          <p>Another fitter has snapped a sensor stem or stripped the nut while changing a tyre. We can fit a programmable replacement and clone the original ID so the car doesn&rsquo;t need a relearn.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="scenario">
          <h3>Winter wheels with no sensors</h3>
          <p>You&rsquo;ve picked up a separate set of winter alloys with no sensors in them. We&rsquo;ll supply, fit and program four matching sensors so the system carries on working through the swap.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-light service-cta-section">
    <div class="container container-narrow text-center">
      <h2>TPMS warning on?</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-dark">Tell us your registration and what the light&rsquo;s doing &mdash; we&rsquo;ll quote on the spot and in most cases get to you the same day. Don&rsquo;t risk an MOT fail.</p>
      <a class="btn btn-primary btn-call" href={telHref}>
        <span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> Call {phone}
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
